Here's how you could write this function in Julia:

```julia
using Statistics

function weather_data_analyzer(temps)
    if isempty(temps)
        return (average=nothing, max=nothing, min=nothing, trend=nothing)
    else
        avg = mean(temps)
        max_temp = maximum(temps)
        min_temp = minimum(temps)

        if all(t -> t > avg, temps)
            return (average=avg, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend=:increasing)
        elseif all(t -> t < avg, temps)
            return (average=avg, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend=:decreasing)
        else
            return (average=avg, max=max_temp, min=min_temp, trend=:stable)
        end
    end
end
```

This function takes in a list of daily temperature data and calculates the average, maximum, minimum temperature. Then it checks if all temperatures are greater than the average or lesser than the average, which is used to determine the trend. If the list of temps is empty, then it returns a named tuple with everything set to `nothing`.
